Loading Dataset & Required Packages¶

In [ ]:
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from sklearn.ensemble import IsolationForest
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings('ignore')

# Load the dataset
file_path = 'Healthcare Providers.csv'
data = pd.read_csv(file_path)

The dataset contains healthcare provider information, including provider details, service codes, and various payment amounts. Here are the main columns:¶

    National Provider Identifier: Unique identifier for each provider.

    Provider Name and Credentials: Name, credentials, and gender of the provider.

    Provider Address: Includes street address, city, state, and ZIP code.

    HCPCS Code and Description: Codes and descriptions for the services provided.

    Number of Services: Count of services provided.

    Medicare Beneficiary Data: Number of Medicare beneficiaries and distinct services per day.

    Payment Data: Various payment-related columns including average allowed amount, submitted charge amount, payment amount, and standardized amount.

Encryption & Decryption¶

In [ ]:
from cryptography.fernet import Fernet
from io import StringIO

# Generate a key for encryption
key = Fernet.generate_key()
cipher_suite = Fernet(key)

# Encrypt the dataset
encrypted_data = cipher_suite.encrypt(data.to_csv(index=False).encode())
print('Data encrypted successfully')

# Decrypt the dataset
print('Decrypting the data...')
decrypted_data = cipher_suite.decrypt(encrypted_data).decode()
data = pd.read_csv(StringIO(decrypted_data))
print('Data decrypted successfully')

Data encrypted successfully
Decrypting the data...
Data decrypted successfully

    plt.xlabel('')
    plt.ylabel('')

plt.show()

Service and Beneficiary Count Relationship:¶

  • The positive correlations between service counts and beneficiary counts suggest that providers with more services tend to have more Medicare beneficiaries and more distinct beneficiaries per day.

Weak Correlations with Number of Services and Beneficiaries:¶

  • The weak correlations between service/beneficiary counts and payment-related columns suggest that the financial metrics are not directly influenced by the volume of services or the number of beneficiaries.

Anomaly Detection using Isolation Forest¶

  • In the context of Isolation Forest, the prediction labels are as follows:

      -1: Indicates an anomaly 
  1: Indicates a normal data point
In [ ]:
model = IsolationForest(contamination=0.01)
data['Anomaly'] = model.fit_predict(data[numeric_columns])

# Plot anomalies
anomalies = data[data['Anomaly'] == -1]
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))
plt.suptitle('Anomalies in the Data')
for i, col in enumerate(numeric_columns, 1):
    plt.subplot(3, 3, i)
    sns.scatterplot(data=data, x=data.index, y=col, hue='Anomaly', palette={-1: 'red', 1: 'blue'})
    plt.title(f'{col}')
    plt.xlabel('')
    plt.ylabel('')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Anomaly Detection Using DBSCAN¶

In [ ]:
import numpy as np
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

# Select numeric columns for scaling
numeric_cols = data.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns.tolist()

# Standardize features
scaler = StandardScaler()
scaled_features = scaler.fit_transform(data[numeric_cols])

# Convert scaled features back to a DataFrame
df_scaled = pd.DataFrame(scaled_features, columns=numeric_cols)

from sklearn.cluster import DBSCAN

dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=0.5, min_samples=5)

# Fit the model
dbscan.fit(df_scaled)

# Predict clusters
data['cluster'] = dbscan.labels_

# Identify anomalies (cluster label -1 indicates an anomaly)
data['anomaly_db'] = data['cluster'].apply(lambda x: 1 if x == -1 else 0)
In [ ]:
# Get the common indices between df_scaled and data
common_indices = df_scaled.index.intersection(data.index)

# Use only the common indices in both dataframes
df_scaled = df_scaled.loc[common_indices]
data = data.loc[common_indices]

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
sns.scatterplot(x=data.index, y=df_scaled[numeric_cols[0]], hue=data['anomaly_db'], palette=['blue', 'red'])
plt.title('Fraud Detection in Healthcare Providers Data')
plt.xlabel('Index')
plt.ylabel(numeric_cols[0])
plt.show()
